 <title>WBU-16-0001 - In the Matter Robert Schweiger</title>
 <link>https://energy.gov/oha/downloads/wbu-16-0001-matter-robert-schweiger</link>
 <description>&lt;a href=&quot;/oha/downloads/wbu-16-0001-matter-robert-schweiger&quot; class=&quot;title-link&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;WBU-16-0001 - In the Matter Robert Schweiger&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div  property=&quot;content:encoded&quot; class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt;On March 4, 2016, OHA denied an Appeal of a dismissal of a Complaint filed by Robert Schweiger against Bechtel National, Inc. (BNI) under the Department of Energy’s (DOE) Contractor Employee Protection Program, 10 C.F.R. Part 708.  In his Complaint, Mr. Schweiger alleged that BNI denied him training, treated him disrespectfully and ultimately terminated him because he had complained about the quality of his supervisor and BNI management, and because he had revealed that he acted as a whistleblower under a different employer about 20 years earlier. The DOE’s Office of River Protection (ORP), citing 10 C.F.R. § 708.17(c)(2), found Mr. Schweiger had failed to state a claim upon which relief could be granted.  It therefore dismissed the Complaint due to lack of jurisdiction.  On appeal, OHA agreed with the ORP that Mr. Schweiger had failed to state a claim upon which relief could be granted.  Specifically, OHA found that Mr. Schweiger’s alleged disclosures did not constitute protected disclosures under Part 708. Consequently, OHA denied Mr. Schweiger’s Appeal. &lt;/p&gt;
